The paper deals with overfitting in machine learning, specifically in object classification tasks using image features. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of masks to indicate regions of interest in medical images, which could also fall under the computer vision sub-category. The paper also discusses training networks to ignore distracting features, which could fall under the machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The use of saliency maps to visualize the distracting features could also fall under the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the impact of the mask information on generalization accuracy, which could fall under the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
